<td class="mbox-text" style="">The examples and perspective in this article <b>deal primarily with <a href="/wiki/Russia" title="Russia">Russia</a> and do not represent a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Countering_systemic_bias" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Countering systemic bias">worldwide view</a> of the subject</b>. Please <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Business_oligarch&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Business_oligarch&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow">improve this article</a> or discuss the issue on the <a href="/wiki/Talk:Business_oligarch" title="Talk:Business oligarch">talk page</a>.</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Business oligarch</b> is a near-synonym of the term "<a href="/wiki/Business_magnate" title="Business magnate">business magnate</a>". The choice of the word <a href="/wiki/Oligarchy" title="Oligarchy">oligarch</a> denotes the significant influence such wealthy individuals may have on the life of a nation. However, in modern Russia it is very common to apply this term to any business tycoon, regardless of whether or not he or she has real political power.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The term came into wide circulation after the <a href="/wiki/Collapse_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Collapse of the Soviet Union" class="mw-redirect">collapse of the Soviet Union</a>, in reference to a small group of individuals who acquired tremendous wealth, significant political influence and often even have controlled mass media in some post-Soviet republics.</p>
